Even though divorce is far more socially accepted in Latvia than it was a mere decade ago, there is a strong hold of tradition upon persons and their families. What goes for divorce goes for singehood as well – in the eyes of the Latvian society. If well over 50% of the women and just under 60% of men admit to having wished to settle down and have kids at some point in time, then it appears that singleness is regarded as a sort of refusal to assimilate into the matrimonial chambers: you either get married or you are a queer. Marriage is a social norm – singleness is a social setback.

Rebirth of the State

But within the realm of marriage public opinion poll, a new, curious role has begun to emerge, one which is being examined by a number of now divorce lawyers, still hanging on to their sleuth hats, but they are more and more often sharpening their swords: the role of the third party in marriage has become vividly established. In other words – a divorce often involves a woman of dubious morals, her husband and the lawyer.
